\f0\b\fs42 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 4. Audio Velocity Layering\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading80\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 To make the drums sound deeply immersive, your code must vary the note volume (velocity) based on the importance of the beat. In lo-fi music, accent patterns follow these acoustic principles:\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f3\fs22 \AppleTypeServices \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f2\b\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 Downbeats (Step 0, 4, 8, 12):
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774  Should hit hard (Velocity 95 - 105) to establish the driving groove.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f3\fs22 \AppleTypeServices {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f2\b\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 Offbeats & Ghost Notes:
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774  Should hit softly (Velocity 40 - 65) to add subtle texture without muddying the mix.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f3\fs22 \AppleTypeServices {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f2\b\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 Hi-Hats:
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774  Alternate velocities every other step (e.g., strong-weak-strong-weak) to recreate the natural arm movements of a real session drummer.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading80\partightenfactor0
